Form Instructions: Stand, squat down, place hands on floor, kick feet back to plank, do a push-up (optional), jump feet back to hands, explode up into a jump.
Repetition Range: As many reps as possible (AMRAP) in a set time
Modification Options: Step feet back instead of jumping, omit jump
Notes: Focus on proper form and controlled movements.

Form Instructions: Stand upright, jump while spreading legs and raising arms overhead, return to starting position.
Modification Options: Reduce range of motion
Notes: Maintain a steady pace.

Form Instructions: Start in a plank position, alternate driving knees towards chest in a running motion.
Modification Options: Perform on knees
Notes: Engage core and maintain a straight back.

Form Instructions: Stand with feet shoulder-width apart, lower hips as if sitting back in a chair, keep back straight, chest up, return to standing.
Modification Options: Reduce range of motion, use a chair for assistance
Notes: Keep knees in line with toes.

Form Instructions: Stand with feet hip-width apart, barbell over mid-foot, hinge at hips, keep back straight, lift bar by extending hips and knees.
Modification Options: Use lighter weight, trap bar deadlifts
Notes: Maintain a neutral spine throughout the lift.

Form Instructions: Complex movement, consult a coach for proper form.
Modification Options: Use lighter weight, break down into components (clean, press)
Notes: Requires significant technique and mobility. Best learned under supervision.

Form Instructions: Stand with feet slightly wider than shoulder-width, kettlebell in front. Hinge at hips to swing kettlebell back, then drive hips forward to swing kettlebell up to chest height.
Modification Options: Use lighter weight, reduce range of motion
Notes: Maintain a neutral spine and engage the core. The power comes from the hip drive.

Form Instructions: Hold barbell in front rack position, squat down, drive up explosively and press barbell overhead.
Modification Options: Use dumbbells, reduce weight
Notes: Maintain a neutral spine throughout the movement. Ensure proper breathing.

Form Instructions: Load sled appropriately, maintain a low, athletic stance, engage core and drive through legs to push or pull.
Modification Options: Reduce load, distance, or speed
Notes: Focus on maintaining a stable core and proper posture.

Form Instructions: Lie face up with weight in one hand, press weight up, transition from lying to standing, keeping weight overhead, reverse the movement to return to starting position.
Progression Options: Increase weight, use a heavier dumbbell/kettlebell
Modification Options: Use lighter weight, break down the movement into parts
Notes: This exercise requires core strength, stability, and coordination. Start with a light weight and master the movement pattern before increasing the load.

Form Instructions: Position barbell across upper back, stand with feet shoulder-width apart, squat down until thighs are parallel to the floor, keep back straight, chest up, return to standing.
Progression Options: Increase weight, add reps, reduce rest time, vary stance
Modification Options: Goblet Squat, Box Squat
Notes: Ensure proper bar placement, maintain neutral spine.

Form Instructions: Hold dumbbells at sides, stand with feet shoulder-width apart, squat down until thighs are parallel to the floor, keep back straight, chest up, return to standing.
Progression Options: Increase weight, add reps, progress to barbell squats
Modification Options: Reduce weight, use a chair for assistance
Notes: Keep dumbbells close to sides, maintain neutral spine.

Form Instructions: Step forward with one leg, lowering hips until both knees are bent at a 90-degree angle, keep torso upright, push off front foot to return to starting position, repeat on other side.
Progression Options: Add weight (dumbbells, barbell), increase reps, try walking lunges
Modification Options: Bodyweight lunges, shorter stride length
Notes: Ensure front knee tracks over the toes and does not go past. Maintain an upright torso throughout the exercise.

Form Instructions: Sit on machine, place feet on platform, lower weight by bending knees, push weight back up to starting position.
Modification Options: Reduce weight, adjust foot placement
Notes: Avoid locking knees at the top of the movement.

Form Instructions: Stand in front of a bench with one foot resting on top. Lower your body down until your front knee is bent at a 90-degree angle and your back knee is close to the ground. Drive through the heel of your front foot to return to the starting position.
Progression Options: Increase weight (dumbbells), progress to barbell, increase reps
Modification Options: Bodyweight, reduce range of motion
Notes: Keep torso upright and ensure front knee tracks in line with toes.

Form Instructions: Stand in front of a platform, step one foot firmly onto the platform, press through the heel to lift your body up onto the platform, lower back down under control, repeat on the other side.
Modification Options: Use a lower platform
Notes: Keep your core engaged and back straight throughout the exercise. Focus on using your leg muscles to lift your body, rather than pushing off the ground with your trailing leg.

Form Instructions: Position yourself on the machine with shoulders under pads, stand with feet shoulder-width apart, lower weight by bending knees, push weight back up to starting position.
Modification Options: Reduce weight
Notes: Keep back flat against pad, avoid locking knees.

Form Instructions: Support barbell across front of shoulders, stand with feet shoulder-width apart, squat down until thighs are parallel to the floor, keep back straight, chest up, return to standing.
Modification Options: Goblet Squat
Notes: Requires good wrist and upper back mobility, maintain upright torso.

Form Instructions: Hold a dumbbell or kettlebell vertically in front of your chest, close to your body. Stand with your feet slightly wider than shoulder-width apart, toes slightly pointed out. Keeping your back straight and core engaged, squat down until your thighs are parallel to the ground or lower. Drive through your heels to return to the starting position.
Progression Options: Increase weight, increase reps, progress to barbell front squats
Modification Options: Reduce weight, use a lighter dumbbell/kettlebell
Notes: The goblet squat is a great exercise for beginners as it helps improve squat form and mobility.

Form Instructions: Set up a box or platform behind you at knee height (or slightly lower). Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, toes slightly pointed out, with the box directly behind you. Hold a barbell across your upper back (as in a back squat). Keeping your core engaged and back straight, slowly lower yourself down until you sit back onto the box. Pause briefly on the box, then drive through your heels to return to a standing position.
Progression Options: Increase weight, increase reps, use a lower box
Modification Options: Reduce weight, use a higher box
Notes: Box squats can help improve squat technique and explosiveness. Ensure proper form and depth before adding significant weight.

Form Instructions: Stand with feet hip-width apart, holding the weight (barbell, dumbbells, or kettlebells) in front of your thighs. Keeping your back straight and core engaged, hinge at your hips and lower the weight towards the ground. Maintain a slight bend in your knees throughout the movement. Lower the weight until you feel a stretch in your hamstrings, then drive your hips forward to return to the starting position.
Progression Options: Increase weight, increase reps, slower tempo
Modification Options: Lighter weight, reduced range of motion
Notes: Focus on maintaining a neutral spine throughout the exercise. The movement should be initiated from the hips, not the lower back.

Form Instructions: Stand with your feet hip-width apart, with the barbell over your mid-foot. Squat down and grip the barbell with an overhand grip, slightly wider than shoulder-width apart. Keep your back straight, chest up, and core engaged. Lift the bar off the ground by extending your hips and knees simultaneously. Pull the bar up close to your body, maintaining a straight back throughout the lift. Lower the barbell back to the ground by reversing the movement.
Progression Options: Increase weight, add reps, deficit deadlifts (standing on a platform)
Modification Options: Trap bar deadlifts, rack pulls (lifting from a raised position)
Notes: The conventional deadlift is a highly technical lift. It is important to use proper form to avoid injury. Consult with a qualified strength coach to learn the correct technique.

Form Instructions: Stand with your feet wider than shoulder-width apart, toes pointed outwards. The barbell should be positioned over your mid-foot. Squat down and grip the barbell with a narrow overhand grip, inside your legs. Keep your back straight, chest up, and core engaged. Lower your hips until your thighs are parallel to the ground. Drive through your heels and extend your hips and knees to lift the barbell off the ground. Pull the bar in close to your body as you lift.  Lower the barbell back to the ground by reversing the movement.
Progression Options: Increase weight, increase reps, pause at the bottom
Modification Options: Use a trap bar, reduce weight
Notes: The Sumo Deadlift is a variation of the traditional deadlift that emphasizes the glutes, hamstrings, and inner thighs. It's important to use proper form and start with a weight that you can handle comfortably.

Form Instructions: Adjust the machine to your height and desired weight. Lie face down on the machine with your legs extended and the ankle pads resting just above your heels. Curl your feet towards your glutes, contracting your hamstrings. Slowly lower the weight back to the starting position.
Progression Options: Increase weight, increase reps, slower tempo
Modification Options: Reduce weight, use one leg at a time
Notes: Focus on isolating the hamstrings and avoid using momentum. Keep your core engaged throughout the exercise.

Form Instructions: Adjust the GHD machine so that your hips are positioned comfortably on the pad. Secure your feet under the foot rollers. Start in an upright position, with your body in a straight line from head to heels. Slowly lower your upper body towards the ground, keeping your back straight. Once you reach your maximum range of motion, use your hamstrings and glutes to pull yourself back up to the starting position.
Progression Options: Add weight (hold a weight plate or wear a weight vest), increase reps
Modification Options: Perform with assistance (using bands or a partner)
Notes: The GHR is a challenging exercise that requires significant hamstring and glute strength. Start with bodyweight and focus on proper form before adding weight.

Form Instructions: Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, with a barbell positioned across your upper back (as in a back squat). Keep your back straight, core engaged, and chest up. Hinge at your hips, pushing your glutes back, and lower your torso towards the ground. Maintain a slight bend in your knees throughout the movement. Lower your torso until you feel a stretch in your hamstrings, then drive your hips forward to return to the starting position.
Progression Options: Increase weight, increase reps, slower tempo
Modification Options: Use lighter weight, perform with a resistance band
Notes: Good Mornings can be challenging on the lower back. Ensure you use proper form and start with a light weight to avoid injury.

Form Instructions: Sit with your upper back against a bench, feet flat on the floor. Drive through your heels to raise your hips, squeezing your glutes at the top.
Progression Options: Increase weight, add resistance bands, single-leg variations
Modification Options: Glute bridges (bodyweight), hip thrusts with reduced range of motion
Notes: Focus on hip drive and glute contraction.

Form Instructions: Stand facing away from a cable machine. Hinge at your hips and pull the rope through your legs, keeping your back straight.
Progression Options: Increase weight, use a resistance band for added challenge
Modification Options: N/A
Notes: Maintain a neutral spine throughout the movement.

Form Instructions: Stand on one leg, hinge at your hips, and lower the weight towards the ground. Keep your back straight and core engaged.
Progression Options: Increase weight, use a barbell, hold weight in one hand
Modification Options: Perform without weight, use a wall or chair for balance
Notes: Focus on balance and control throughout the movement.

Form Instructions: Lie on your back with knees bent and feet flat on the floor. Lift your hips off the ground, squeezing your glutes at the top.
Progression Options: Add weight (plate on hips), single-leg glute bridges
Modification Options: N/A
Notes: Focus on driving through your heels and squeezing your glutes at the top.

Form Instructions: Attach an ankle strap to a low cable pulley. Stand facing the machine and extend one leg back, keeping your core engaged.
Modification Options: N/A
Notes: Focus on squeezing your glutes at the top of the movement.

Form Instructions: Start on your hands and knees. Keeping your knee bent, lift one leg up towards the ceiling, squeezing your glutes at the top.
Progression Options: Add ankle weights, use resistance bands
Modification Options: N/A
Notes: Focus on contracting your glutes to lift your leg, rather than using your back.

Equipment Required: Bodyweight (can use a step or platform)
Form Instructions: Stand with feet hip-width apart, raise up onto the balls of your feet, then lower back down.
Progression Options: Add weight (hold dumbbells), use a calf raise machine
Modification Options: Seated calf raises (emphasize Soleus)
Notes: Focus on full range of motion, from a stretched calf to a peak contraction.

Form Instructions: Bend over at the waist, have a partner sit on your lower back (or hold weight), then perform calf raises.
Progression Options: Have your partner add weight, or hold heavier dumbbells.
Modification Options: Use a donkey calf raise machine
Notes: Keep your back straight and core engaged.

Form Instructions: Position yourself under the Smith Machine bar (similar to a squat). Perform calf raises.
Modification Options: Use a block under your toes to increase range of motion.
Notes: Keep your back straight and core engaged.

Form Instructions: Hold heavy dumbbells in each hand and walk on your toes for a certain distance or time.
Duration: Can be incorporated into a circuit
Modification Options: Use lighter weights, shorten the distance.
Notes: Keep your core engaged and maintain an upright posture.

Form Instructions: Lie on a bench with feet flat on the floor. Unrack the barbell, lower it to your chest, and press back up.
Progression Options: Increase weight, add pause reps, decline bench press
Modification Options: Dumbbell bench press, push-ups
Notes: Maintain a slight arch in your back and keep your elbows tucked at a 45-degree angle.

Form Instructions: Place hands shoulder-width apart on the floor, lower your body until your chest touches the floor, and push back up.
Repetition Range: As many reps as possible (AMRAP), or sets of 8-12 reps
Progression Options: Decline push-ups, diamond push-ups, plyometric push-ups
Modification Options: Knee push-ups, wall push-ups
Notes: Keep your core engaged and maintain a straight line from your head to your heels.

Form Instructions: Lie on a bench with feet flat on the floor. Hold a dumbbell in each hand, lower them to your chest, and press back up.
Progression Options: Increase weight, use a decline bench
Modification Options: N/A
Notes: Keep your elbows slightly bent and maintain control of the dumbbells throughout the movement.

Equipment Required: Dumbbells, Cables, or Pec Deck Machine
Form Instructions: (Dumbbell Example) Lie on a bench with feet flat on the floor. Hold dumbbells with a slight bend in your elbows. Lower the dumbbells out to the sides in a wide arc, then bring them back together.
Progression Options: Increase weight (dumbbells, cables), adjust machine resistance
Modification Options: Perform one arm at a time to reduce strain.
Notes: Focus on feeling a stretch in your chest as you lower the weight and squeeze your chest muscles as you bring the weight back up.

Form Instructions: Grip parallel bars with hands slightly wider than shoulder-width. Lower your body until your elbows are bent at a 90-degree angle, then push back up.
Repetition Range: As many reps as possible (AMRAP), or sets of 6-10 reps
Modification Options: Assisted dip machine, bench dips (easier)
Notes: Lean forward slightly to emphasize chest activation. Keep your shoulders down and away from your ears.

Form Instructions: Adjust the seat height so that your elbows are aligned with the machine's pivots. Press your chest forward, bringing the handles together.
Modification Options: N/A
Notes: Focus on squeezing your chest muscles at the peak of the contraction.

Form Instructions: Stand with feet shoulder-width apart, holding cable handles with a slight bend in your elbows. Bring your hands together in front of your body, keeping a slight arc in your arms.
Progression Options: Increase weight, use different cable heights to target different areas of the chest
Modification Options: N/A
Notes: Maintain a slight bend in your elbows throughout the exercise.

Form Instructions: Load one end of a barbell into a landmine attachment. Hold the other end of the barbell with both hands. Press the barbell up and away from your body in an arc.
Progression Options: Increase weight, use one arm at a time
Modification Options: Kneeling landmine press
Notes: Keep your core engaged throughout the exercise.

Difficulty Level: Intermediate to Advanced (variations for different levels)
Form Instructions: Grab a pull-up bar with an overhand grip, slightly wider than shoulder-width apart. Hang with arms fully extended. Pull yourself up until your chin is over the bar, then lower back down.
Repetition Range: As many reps as possible (AMRAP), or sets of 5-8 reps (strength), 8-12 reps (hypertrophy)
Progression Options: Add weight (weight belt), close-grip pull-ups, muscle-ups
Modification Options: Assisted pull-up machine, resistance band pull-ups, negative pull-ups
Notes: Focus on pulling with your back muscles, not just your arms. Keep your core engaged.

Form Instructions: Sit at a lat pulldown machine with a wide grip on the bar. Pull the bar down towards your chest, keeping your back straight. Slowly release the bar back to the starting position.
Progression Options: Increase weight, use a close-grip attachment
Modification Options: N/A
Notes: Keep your chest up and core engaged throughout the movement.

Form Instructions: Stand with feet shoulder-width apart, bend at your hips (back straight). Pull the weight up towards your chest, keeping elbows close to your body. Lower the weight back down.
Progression Options: Increase weight, use a Pendlay row variation (barbell starts on the floor), use dumbbells
Modification Options: Chest-supported rows (e.g., on an incline bench)
Notes: Maintain a flat back throughout the exercise. If using a barbell, consider using an overhand or underhand grip.

Form Instructions: Load the T-Bar machine and position yourself with your chest against the pad. Pull the handles towards your chest, keeping your back straight. Slowly lower the weight back down.
Modification Options: N/A
Notes: Keep your core engaged and avoid using momentum.

Form Instructions: Place one knee and hand on a bench, keeping your back straight. Hold a dumbbell in your other hand and let it hang down. Pull the dumbbell up towards your chest, keeping your elbow close to your body.
Modification Options: Use lighter weight, focus on control
Notes: Maintain a flat back throughout the exercise. Engage your core to prevent twisting.

Equipment Required: Cable Machine, V-Bar or Rope Attachment
Form Instructions: Sit with feet on the platform, knees slightly bent, grasp the attachment. Keep back straight, pull the handle towards your abdomen. Control the weight back to starting position.
Progression Options: Increase weight, use different attachments for variations
Modification Options: N/A
Notes: Maintain good posture throughout, focus on squeezing your back muscles during the pull.

Equipment Required: Smith Machine or Barbell (set at waist height)
Form Instructions: Lie under the bar (overhand grip, slightly wider than shoulder-width). Body straight, heels on the ground. Pull your chest towards the bar, then lower slowly.
Repetition Range: As many reps as possible (AMRAP), or sets of 8-12 reps
Progression Options: Elevate feet, add weight (weight vest/plate on hips)
Modification Options: Perform with knees bent to make it easier.
Notes: Maintain a straight line from head to toe throughout the exercise. Engage your core.

Form Instructions: Stand with feet shoulder-width apart, holding weight with a neutral grip. Raise your shoulders straight up as high as possible. Slowly lower back down.
Modification Options: Use dumbbells for a greater range of motion.
Notes: Avoid rolling your shoulders. Focus on a straight up-and-down movement.

Form Instructions: Position yourself on a hyperextension bench. Lower your upper body down towards the floor. Engage your lower back muscles to raise your upper body back up to a straight line.
Progression Options: Hold a weight plate or dumbbell close to your chest.
Modification Options: Reduce range of motion if needed.
Notes: Focus on a controlled movement, avoiding any jerking or using momentum.

Form Instructions: Stand with feet hip-width apart, bar on rack at knee level. Hinge at hips to grab bar, shoulder-width grip. Keep back straight, pull bar up, squeezing shoulder blades. Lower bar slowly to starting position.
Progression Options: Increase weight, add reps, reduce rest time
Modification Options: Use lighter weight, elevate bar position
Notes: Maintain a neutral spine, avoid rounding the back

Form Instructions: Stand with feet shoulder-width apart, holding weight slightly above shoulders. Brace core, press weight straight overhead until arms are fully extended. Lower weight slowly to starting position.
Progression Options: Increase weight, add reps, reduce rest time
Modification Options: Use lighter weight, seated variation
Notes: Avoid arching lower back, keep core engaged

Form Instructions: Sit with back straight, hold dumbbells with palms facing body. Curl dumbbells up while rotating wrists outwards. Lower weights back to starting position, reversing rotation.
Modification Options: Use lighter weight, perform one arm at a time
Notes: Control the weight throughout the movement

Form Instructions: Stand with feet shoulder-width apart, slight bend in elbows. Raise arms to sides until elbows are at shoulder height. Lower weights slowly to starting position.
Modification Options: Use lighter weight, seated variation
Notes: Maintain slight bend in elbows, avoid swinging weights

Form Instructions: Stand with feet shoulder-width apart, hold weight with an overhand grip. Raise weight in front of you to shoulder height, keeping elbows slightly bent. Lower weight slowly to starting position.
Modification Options: Use lighter weight, alternate arms
Notes: Avoid swinging the weight, maintain a controlled movement

Form Instructions: Sit or stand with bent knees, hinge at hips with a flat back. Let arms hang down with slight bend in elbows. Raise dumbbells to sides, squeezing shoulder blades together. Slowly lower weights to starting position.
Modification Options: Use lighter weight, perform one arm at a time
Notes: Focus on squeezing shoulder blades at the top of the movement

Form Instructions: Stand with feet shoulder-width apart, holding weight with an overhand grip. Pull weight up towards chin, keeping close to body. Lower weight slowly to starting position.
Progression Options: Increase weight, add reps, reduce rest time
Modification Options: Use lighter weight, wider grip
Notes: Avoid using momentum, focus on controlled movement

Form Instructions: Stand facing cable machine, grab rope attachment with overhand grip. Pull rope towards face, keeping elbows high and wide. Reverse movement to return to starting position.
Modification Options: Use lighter weight, adjust cable height
Notes: Focus on pulling through elbows, keep shoulders down and back

Form Instructions: Stand with feet shoulder-width apart, hold weight with underhand grip. Curl weight towards shoulders, keeping elbows tucked. Slowly lower weight back to starting position.
Progression Options: Increase weight, add reps, reduce rest time
Modification Options: Use lighter weight, alternate arms
Notes: Avoid swinging the weight, focus on controlled movement

Form Instructions: Stand with feet shoulder-width apart, hold dumbbells with neutral grip. Curl dumbbells towards shoulders, keeping palms facing each other. Slowly lower weights back to starting position.
Progression Options: Increase weight, add reps, reduce rest time
Modification Options: Use lighter weight, alternate arms
Notes: Maintain a neutral grip throughout the exercise

Equipment Required: Dumbbell or Barbell, Preacher Curl Bench
Form Instructions: Sit on preacher curl bench with upper arms resting on pad. Hold dumbbell or barbell with underhand grip. Curl weight towards shoulders, keeping elbows tucked. Slowly lower weight back to starting position.
Progression Options: Increase weight, add reps, reduce rest time
Modification Options: Use lighter weight, adjust seat height
Notes: Keep elbows tucked, avoid swinging the weight

Form Instructions: Sit on bench with feet flat on floor, hold dumbbell in one hand. Rest elbow on inner thigh, let weight hang down. Curl dumbbell towards shoulder, keeping elbow stationary. Slowly lower weight back to starting position.
Progression Options: Increase weight, add reps, reduce rest time
Modification Options: Use lighter weight
Notes: Keep back straight, avoid using momentum

Form Instructions: Grip parallel bars or bench with hands shoulder-width apart. Lower body by bending elbows until they're at a 90-degree angle. Push back up to starting position, extending arms fully.
Modification Options: Perform dips on a bench for easier variation
Notes: Keep elbows close to body, avoid flaring them out

Form Instructions: Lie on bench with feet flat on floor, hold weight with overhand grip. Lower weight towards forehead, keeping elbows tucked. Extend arms back to starting position, squeezing triceps.
Progression Options: Increase weight, add reps, reduce rest time
Modification Options: Use lighter weight, perform with dumbbells for more stability
Notes: Keep elbows stationary, avoid flaring them out

Form Instructions: Stand facing cable machine, grab attachment with overhand grip. Keep elbows tucked, push attachment down until arms are fully extended. Slowly return to starting position.
Progression Options: Increase weight, add reps, reduce rest time
Modification Options: Use lighter weight, adjust cable height
Notes: Keep elbows stationary, focus on squeezing triceps at the bottom of the movement

Form Instructions: Lie on bench with feet flat on floor, hold barbell with a close overhand grip. Lower barbell to chest, keeping elbows tucked. Push barbell back to starting position, extending arms fully.
Progression Options: Increase weight, add reps, reduce rest time
Modification Options: Use lighter weight, perform with dumbbells for more stability
Notes: Keep wrists straight, avoid flaring elbows out

Form Instructions: Stand with feet shoulder-width apart, hold dumbbell or cable attachment overhead with both hands. Lower weight behind head, keeping elbows close to ears. Extend arms back to starting position, squeezing triceps.
Progression Options: Increase weight, add reps, reduce rest time
Modification Options: Use lighter weight, perform one arm at a time
Notes: Keep elbows stationary, avoid arching back

Form Instructions: Stand with feet shoulder-width apart, hold weight with overhand grip. Curl weight upwards, keeping elbows tucked. Slowly lower weight back to starting position.
Progression Options: Increase weight, add reps, reduce rest time
Modification Options: Use lighter weight, alternate arms
Notes: Keep wrists straight, avoid swinging the weight

Form Instructions: Sit on bench with forearms resting on thighs, wrists hanging off edge. Hold weight with underhand grip. Curl weight upwards, flexing wrists. Slowly lower weight back to starting position.
Progression Options: Increase weight, add reps, reduce rest time
Modification Options: Use lighter weight
Notes: Keep wrists straight, avoid moving elbows

Form Instructions: Sit on bench with forearms resting on thighs, wrists hanging off edge. Hold weight with overhand grip. Curl weight upwards, extending wrists. Slowly lower weight back to starting position.
Progression Options: Increase weight, add reps, reduce rest time
Modification Options: Use lighter weight
Notes: Keep wrists straight, avoid moving elbows

Form Instructions: Place forearms on floor, elbows under shoulders, body in straight line from head to heels. Hold position, engaging core.
Progression Options: Increase hold time, add weight plate to back
Modification Options: Perform on knees, against wall
Notes: Maintain neutral spine, avoid sagging hips

Form Instructions: Lie on side, prop body up on elbow and forearm. Stack feet, raise hips off ground, forming straight line from head to heels. Hold position, engaging core.
Progression Options: Increase hold time, add weight plate to hip
Modification Options: Perform with knees bent
Notes: Maintain straight line, avoid sagging hips

Form Instructions: Assume plank position. Have partner place weight plate on upper back. Hold position, engaging core.
Modification Options: Use lighter weight, reduce hold time
Notes: Ensure weight is evenly distributed, maintain proper form

Form Instructions: Lie on back, knees bent, feet flat on floor. Cross arms over chest. Engage core, lift upper body towards thighs. Lower back down slowly.
Modification Options: Crunches, hands behind head for support
Notes: Avoid pulling on neck, focus on abdominal contraction

Form Instructions: Lie on back, knees bent, feet flat on floor. Place hands behind head for support. Engage core, lift head and shoulders off ground. Lower back down slowly.
Modification Options: Hands on chest, focus on controlled movement
Notes: Avoid pulling on neck, engage core throughout

Form Instructions: Lie on back, knees bent, feet flat on floor. Place hands behind head for support. Engage core, lift one knee towards chest while twisting upper body to opposite side. Alternate sides in a cycling motion.
Modification Options: Focus on one side at a time
Notes: Maintain controlled movement, avoid pulling on neck

Form Instructions: Lie on back, knees bent, feet flat on floor. Place hands behind head for support. Engage core, lift hips off ground, bringing knees towards chest. Lower back down slowly.
Modification Options: Hands under glutes for support
Notes: Avoid swinging legs, focus on controlled movement

Form Instructions: Lie on back, legs straight, hands under glutes for support. Engage core, lift legs towards ceiling. Lower legs back down slowly without arching back.
Modification Options: Bent knees, lower legs to halfway point
Notes: Avoid arching lower back, focus on controlled movement

Form Instructions: Hang from pull-up bar with overhand grip. Engage core, lift legs towards chest. Lower legs back down slowly without swinging.
Modification Options: Bent knees, knee raises
Notes: Avoid swinging, engage core throughout

Equipment Required: Bodyweight (can use medicine ball or weight plate)
Form Instructions: Sit with knees bent, heels on floor, torso leaning back. Twist torso side to side, touching the weight or hands to the floor on each side.
Modification Options: Keep feet on floor for easier variation
Notes: Engage core throughout the movement.

Form Instructions: Lie face up, arms extended overhead. Simultaneously raise legs and torso, reaching hands towards toes. Lower back down with control.
Modification Options: Bend knees slightly
Notes: Maintain controlled movement throughout.

Form Instructions: Lie face down on a bench, gripping the edge behind your head. Raise your body into a straight line, using your core. Lower down slowly and with control.
Modification Options: Perform knee raises instead
Notes: This is an advanced exercise, work up to it gradually.

Form Instructions: Kneel facing the cable machine, holding the rope behind your head. Contract your abs to bring your elbows towards your knees. Control the movement back to the starting position.
Modification Options: Decrease weight for easier variation
Notes: Focus on squeezing your abs at the top of the movement.

Form Instructions: Hang from a pull-up bar with an overhand grip. Keeping your legs together, raise your knees towards your chest. Lower back down with control.
Modification Options: Bend knees to 90 degrees
Notes: Avoid swinging your body during the movement.

Form Instructions: Lie face up with arms extended towards the ceiling and legs bent to 90 degrees. Lower one arm and the opposite leg towards the floor while maintaining contact between your lower back and the ground. Return to starting position and repeat on the other side.
Progression Options: Hold a weight in each hand
Modification Options: Keep feet on the floor for easier variation
Notes: Focus on keeping your core engaged throughout the entire exercise.

Form Instructions: Lie face up with arms extended overhead and legs straight. Engage your core and press your lower back into the ground. Lift your legs and shoulders slightly off the ground, maintaining a hollow body position. Hold for time.
Modification Options: Bend your knees or keep your arms by your side for an easier variation
Notes: Maintain a tight core throughout the hold.

Form Instructions: Kneel on the floor with the ab wheel in front of you. Keeping your core engaged, slowly roll the wheel forward, extending your body. Roll back to the starting position with control.
Modification Options: Roll out a shorter distance
Notes: Maintain a neutral spine throughout the movement.

Form Instructions: Maintain upright posture, engage core, controlled stride
Calories Burned Estimate: Highly variable based on pace and duration
Modification Options: Walk breaks, shorter duration
Notes: Proper footwear is essential, listen to your body

Form Instructions: Maintain a comfortable posture, engage core, pedal smoothly
Calories Burned Estimate: Highly variable based on intensity and duration
Modification Options: Lower resistance, shorter duration
Notes: Stay hydrated, wear appropriate gear

Form Instructions: Maintain proper form, drive with legs, engage core
Calories Burned Estimate: Highly variable based on intensity and duration
Modification Options: Lower resistance, shorter duration
Notes: Focus on smooth, controlled movements

Difficulty Level: Beginner to Advanced (speed and variations vary)
Form Instructions: Maintain light jumps, use wrists for rotation, engage core
Progression Options: Increase speed, try different jump variations
Modification Options: Start with basic jumps, shorter durations
Notes: Good for coordination and agility
